G. i. 2.—This metre takes its name from Sappho. It consists of stanzas of four verses each. The first three are alike, and consist of four trochees, with a dactyl in the third place. Horace always sub- stitutes a spondee for the second trochee, with one uncertain exception, C. S. 70. The fourth verse consiste of a dactyl and spondee, and is named an Adonio.

This is one of the commonest metres. It differs in Horace's hands from the Greek usage by the less frequent introduction of the trochee in the second place, and from the caesura usually falling after the fifth syllable. This arrangement takes away a good deal from the vigour of the metre, a defect which Horace seems to have perceived

when he wrote the Carmen Saeculare and the Sapphic Odes of the fourth book ⁷.
